old tackle rules

Tackling someone is done by moving into base contact, then a resistance roll. Since tackling is such a slow attack, the target has the option to take one action to
attacker : str + speed/3 (round down)
defender : str
If successful, the tackler can move the target out of the way in a direction that makes sense (GM discretion). The maximum distance is 1 + diff/3 round down. Large targets reduce the max distance by one for every square they occupy beyond the first.
Tackling is a slow attack and the defender is allowed to react if he is aware of the incoming attack. He can choose to take one action to "defend" against the attack. If

If successful the tackler can move the target one square out of the way in a direction that makes sense. The attacker must then roll for dex to see if he stands or falls. The target must roll for dex mod -diff to see if he falls.
If failure the attacker must roll for dex mod -diff to see if he falls.







old rule for long term activity

Long term activity
------------------
A character can only be "highly active" for 10*con rounds. He must then rest and let his guard down for 10-con/2 rounds, during which he cannot take actions and cannot move faster than walk or carry anything heavy.
When exceeding this time without resting the character gets modifications to all actions: mod-(excess/10 round up).





old text about actions that take more than one action to perform:

Actions that take more than one action
---------------------------------------
Some actions take two or three actions. Those actions create mod penalties for subsequent actions as though they are several actions.
E.g. a 2action maneuver attack is performed as primary action, first in the round. It takes mod-0 penalty since it is first in the round and the ams is at zero. It pushes mod-6 onto the ams. The following attack action then takes the mod-6 penalty.




old double text, end of skill text

 The parrying actions does not have to be "double", but then normal penalties for multiple actions apply.
E.g: it can be interesting to roll for double when carrying a shield and a sword, just to save on the actions.
It is possible to "save" the other double action, and declare it later. It can be saved until performing another action or movement. E.g: when facing an opponent in melee, the character rolls a successful double, using the axe to make an attack, and saving the sword for a later parry, if the opponent does an immediate counter attack. The "saved parry" is discarded the next time he uses the axe, or moves, or does anything at all in fact.





old timing and pacing rules:    -- replaced by focus --

Skill cost special "timing": allows for a one step re-arrangement of the order of action penalties. E.g. shifting the order of a mod-0 primary action and mod-3 secondary action to get penalty order: mod-3, mod-0, mod-6, mod-9
Each skill level of "timing" can be used to make a one step penalty re-arrangement.
E.g. shifting to mod-3, mod-6, mod-0, mod-9 is a two step re-arrangement.
E.g. shifting to mod-6, mod-3, mod-0, mod-9 is a three step re-arrangement.
Timing level 1 costs 10xp
       level 2 costs 25xp
       level 3 costs 45xp
       level 4 costs 70xp


Skill cost special "pacing": allows for splitting action penalties according to the "mod -(2/3) of highest" rule. Each level of "pacing" allows to make one split. E.g. splitting to get mod-2, mod-2, mod-6, mod-9 is one split.
E.g. splitting to get mod-4, mod-4, mod-4, mod-9 are two splits.
E.g. splitting to get mod-6, mod-6, mod-6, mod-6 are three splits.
The splitting must start at the first non zero mod in the action list, and progress. This also means that the character must plan ahead if he can push actions with different mods on the action mod stack.
Timing level 1 costs 15xp
       level 2 costs 35xp
       level 3 costs 60xp
       level 4 costs 90xp
The resulting mods should be rounded up if they are not even numbers.
If the character also has quick, then the quick penalty reduction can be applied in any order. E.g:
quick 2 then pacing 1:
-0,-3,-6,-9 (quick 2:) -0,-1,-4,-7 (timing 1)















