Old feints finesse and flair text, it is good, but duplicates the info
in the "fancy attacks" skill

Feints, finesse, and flair
--------------------------
Some melee weapons give the possibility of making more difficult attacks that are also more difficult to parry. For each "difficult maneuver" or "feint" mod the attacker takes, the target will get the same mod to his parry roll. This can break the stale mate that will otherwise develop between good fighters that won't miss their attack or parry rolls on normal difficulty.
E.g. Weasly Wesley attacks his skilled opponent with a feint-4. He manages to hit with his roll, and the opponent will now have a mod-4 to his parry.
Some weapons have a finesse limit. E.g. Clubs have finesse-2 as the most difficult and extravagant maneuvers that can be performed, while swords have finesse-6. That means that it is possible to do feints with a mod down to the maximum level. Specialist weapons can have higher finesse, e.g. Long chain flails.





old grapple skill text


Skill scf 0.66 "grapple": is used to hold opponents in body lock so that they cannot move, and get mod-6 penalties on defend and attack actions.
Grappling assumes that the attacker has both hands free. He has a mod-3 to all grapple related rolls if he only uses one hand.

Step 1) Grab Hold:
Roll a grapple attack. If it succeeds and is not parried or avoided, the grappler has managed to lock hold on the target.

If the grapple attack is parried with a weapon, the grappler can choose to grab hold of that weapon (Don't grab a sword. A shield, staff or spear is fine though). Then both parties can try to roll str/str to rip the weapon from each others hands. Tugging at a weapon forces an action on both parties. A success or fail at 3 or greater means that the weapon is lost to the opponent. Just roll once for this, regardless of who initiates.

If the target has grapple he can choose to react with a "counter grapple" instead of avoid or parry. Then it devolves into a resistance roll. Both parties chooses the highest: str or dex, and uses as the stat for the stat vs stat resistance roll. The attacker adds his grapple success to the stat and the target rolls for his grapple and adds the success (not failure) to the stat.
In this case both parties are counted as attackers. If either wins the diff+stat vs diff+stat roll with a +3 or more, he has successfully locked hold of the opponent.

Step 2) Target is held:
Holding a target is primary action each round that starts with the target being held. It is not an extra action after the target has been grappled.
The target can try to break or squirm out of the hold. This is one action. Both the grappler and the target chooses his highest value of str or dex, and uses that for a resistance roll. A success from the target means he breaks free. If he fails he is still held in a lock. Observe that this does not force an extra action onto the grappler.
If the target manages to break free, the grappler can immediately try a reactive (ignoring initiative) new grapple attack with mod+3, to see if he can manage to grab hold of the target again. Observer that this cannot be a primary action, since the grappler has used his primary action trying to already hold the target at the starting of the round.
A target that is held has mod-3 to all actions, except trying to break free. If he tries to use an action that requires two hands he has mod-6.

When a target is held, the grappler can choose to spend one action per round to see if he can inflict some crushing damage on the target. He rolls a str/str roll and the diff is the actual damage he will inflict (i.e. don't roll a damage roll from the result of the str/str, instead, apply the entire diff as damage directly).
dam = str(grappler) - str(target) +5 -d10

Assisting someone to break out of grapple:
Characters assisting a grappled target to break free can add their str/2 round down to the target's strength or dex when he tries to break free. Assisting is a primary action and takes until the target is free, unless interrupted.






old tackle skill text

The target can avoid the tackle or break loose with on a roll for dex mod -diff (tackle success).
The chase roll ignores all movement modifications, but is subject to normal action mod stack penalties.
The chaser can get a mod+3 if he "throws" himself (maneuver) after the target, like in the movies, but then he will fall for sure this round (taking no damage if he succeeds in the tackle, otherwise normal damage) and must get up next round.
A successful "tackle" maneuver means that the target must roll for dex with an extra mod-3 or falls to the ground and must get up next round.
A successful "grab" maneuver means that the chaser can try "grapple action" immediately next round, ignoring initiative.
To simplify the "chase" roll:
chance = chase + (speed diff) + dex/dex


Skill scf 1.0 "tackle": allows to tackle targets to break through blocks, knock targets out of the path, and to gain ground by pushing them away.
The user declares a "tackle advance at speed x" and describes a more or less straight path (GM discretion). He then starts moving along the path. At each base contact (also diagonal) he gets with an opponent he can chose to make a "tackle action" and roll for the tackle of that specific opponent. The tackle action ignores movement penalties, but subject to the action mod stack as usual.

Tackling a target: Running into someone to move them while regaining control.
Roll for tackle. If successful the tackler has retained control and can continue with his movement. If it fails he has still hit his target but lost control and must stop moving, after getting entangled in base contact.
If fail: tackler must roll a dex - diff or fall.

Moving the target: After running into the target it is a resist roll to see if the target moves or not. If the target has tackle or block skill he can choose to take an action to
tackler resist value: diff(tackle) + str + speed/2 (round down)
target resist value:  diff(tackle or block) + str
If success: tackler can move target one square out of the way in a direction that makes sense.

Target falling?: target rolls a


The user declares a "tackle advance at speed x" and describes a more or less straight path (GM discretion). He then starts moving along the path. At each base contact (also diagonal) he gets with an opponent he can chose to make a "tackle action" and roll for the tackle of that specific opponent. The tackle action ignores movement penalties, but subject to the action mod stack as usual.

If the tackle attack roll fails the tackler can either continue to the next target in the path, or he can choose to stop.
The target can of course choose to interrupt or react to the tackle attack action based on initiative.
If the tackle roll fails-3 the tackler must roll a dex or fall.
If the tackle roll fails-6 the tackler must roll a dex-3 or fall.
If the tackle roll fails-9 the tackler falls.

The target can spend an action to try to resist the tackle. If he resists he stands his ground.
Resistance roll:
tackler resist value:   diff(tackle roll) + str + speed/2 (round down)
target resist value:    (diff tackle or block) + str
If the defender has tackle or block he can roll for that and add the diff to his own resist value in the resistance roll.

The result of the tackle, or resistance roll if the target resisted:
success : the tackler can move the target one square out of the way, in such a way as makes sense.
success+3 : the target must roll a dex or fall
success+6 : the target must roll a

The resistance roll decides the outcome of the tackle attack action:
If the attacker succeeds he can choose to move the defender out of the way one square. If moved, the defender must roll a dex mod (resistance roll diff) or be off balance even if he has movement points left. If he has no movement points left he will off balance.
If the attacker succeeds+3 the defender must roll a dex-3 or fall.
If the attacker succeeds+6 the defender must roll a dex-6 or fall and take 1d3 damage.
If the attacker succeeds+9 the defender must roll a dex-9 or fall and take 1d6 damage.







old encumbrance text

A character can carry up to his strength in "encumbrance points" without penalty. Each exceeded multiple of strength yields a mod-1 to all actions. This is approximately the same as mod = load / strength (round down).
Also, stuff has to be carried somewhere. "Item Slots" are hands, carried over shoulders, hung in belt, put in sacks, etc. Different clothing and carry items allow for different amount of slots.
E.g: ruck sack 5 items, belt 2 items, belt 4 items,
Carrying a heavy load also makes it more demanding to run and dash.
dash requires enc/str round down extra stamina each round.
run requires end/(2 * str) round down extra stamina each round.




old stat roll rules


Stat rolls
----------
Some typical stat rolls, not directly related to actions or maneuvers.

Strength (str) rolls:
1) Break down that door!

Dexterity (dex) rolls:
1) running on bad ground, e.g. rubble: light rubble mod+3, rubble mod-0, heavy rubble mod-3. Dashing on bad ground is mod-3, relative to run. Walking is mod+3 relative to run.
One roll per square. Missed dex rolls while running means falling down. Falling while walking means falling on the fail square. Falling while running means falling down on the next square, and taking 1 damage penetrating 1. Falling while dashing means falling two squares away and taking 1d3 damage, penetrating 1.

Constitution (con) rolls:
1) often used for vs rolls against poisons, disease, etc.

Psyche (psy) rolls:
1) when facing a superior foe or force, or when your friends are dying around you, or when you are taking lots of damage. Time to see if you will stand your ground, advance or flee. The "veteran" skill will cancel a lot of modifications here.
Mods are influenced by situation. 50% hp or below mod-1, 75% hp or below mod-3. Superior force mod-0, 2x superior force mod-3, 4x superior force mod-6. Superior force is calculated by total strength stats, or just body numbers if similar character.
Rolls will be called by GM every now and then.
A fail means you cannot advance, but can stand your ground.
A fail-3 or worse means you will retreat.
A fail-6 or worse means you will flee, and must do an int roll to see if you can think of the best way, instead of just away.
A fail-9 or worse means you will flee, dropping all discardable equipment, etc, and will have a mod-3 to the int roll to see if it is a good direction

Perception (per) rolls:
1) Do you notice the sneaky thief, or the hiding goblin?

Charisma (cha) rolls:
1) Can you dissuade the old witch to not toast you alive?




rules for bows and crossbows

Bows and Arrows
---------------
Bows have a limited rate of fire, but cannot generally be parried, and have a good range.
Bows are normally fired at the end of a round, after a full round "shot".
The next round is spent reloading the bow.
The skills "quick shot" and "rapid reload bow" can compress the times for shooting and reloading. The "sniper" skill can reduce modifications for range.
A "loaded" bow is notched and drawn. Keeping a bow drawn can be maintained at most con rounds. After that it requires one stamina each round.
A bow can be kept notch but not drawn. Drawing a bow takes 1a, or rest of round regardless of ams.


Crossbows
---------
Crossbows take a long time reload. Usually a couple of rounds. Snap shot, normal shot, and aimed shots usually take the same time as bows.
The benefits over the bow is that is does more damage, and can be fired directly after being drawn/readied, without the reload round in between. It is also significantly cheaper to learn the skill.
The skill "rapid reload crossbow" can reduce reload times.






skip rapid reload in this form, rewrite with compounded rate of fire rules.

Skill scf special "rapid reload bow": can reload a bow faster, and in "rest of round" with more penalties on the action mod stack.
lvl 1 (cost 10): reload bow in 2 actions, or "rest of round" with maximum action mod stack at mod-3.
lvl 2 (cost 15): reload bow in 2 actions, or "rest of round" with maximum action mod stack at mod-6.
lvl 3 (cost 25): reload bow in 1 action, or "rest of round" with maximum action mod stack at mod-9.
lvl 4 (cost 35): reload bow in 1 action, or "rest of round" with maximum action mod stack at mod-12.
lvl 5 (cost 50): reload bow in 0 action, pushing no mod on the action mod stack.


Skill scf special "rapid reload crossbow": can reload crossbow type weapon (crossbow, arbalest, ballista (obs, ballista takes 2ppl)) faster than usual. Each skill level reduces the time to reload, according to table below.
lvl cost     crossbow      h.crossbow      arbalest    l.ballista   ballista
 1   10         2              4              6             8          16
 2   20         1              3              5             7          14
 3   30    2a,ror:mams-3       2              4             6          12
 4   40    2a,ror:mams-6       1              3             5          10
 5   50    1a,ror:mams-9  2a,ror:mams-3       2             4           8
 6   60    1a,ror:mams-12 2a,ror:mams-6       1             3           6
 7   70     0a, no mod    1a,ror:mams-9  2a,ror:mams-3      2           4
 8   80                   1a,ror:mams-12 2a,ror:mams-6      1           3
