skip max mams skill now.

Skill scf 1.0 "max mams": Each level of "max mams" gives one extra point "MAMS" allowance for actions and maneuvers that have MAMS limitations.





old hits and damage rules, now in skills

Good hits and Great hits         (really use this ??)
------------------------
A good hit (success+3) is -1 to parry.
A very good hit (success+6) is -2 to parry.
A perfect hit (success+9) is -3 to parry.
A very good hit does at least half the damage of the weapon, rounded down.
A perfect hit also does full damage of the weapon.



from actions that take more than one action

Also, their penalties cannot be shifted around, but the action will take and yield penalties in the order they are performed.

 The primary-ness and secondary-ness cannot be shifted for this purpose.

 E.g. A primary attack is done with mod-0, then a 2action action is taken as secondary action



old stuff about not being able to shuffle mods on actions that don't require rolls:

Actions that does not requires rolls
------------------------------------
Some actions, like rapid drawing of throwing knives, takes an action but does not require a roll. The natural Munchkin move would of course be to push that action to take the heaviest mod in the round. That is not allowed. Muahaha.
Since drawing a knife comes before throwing the knife, it will push one regular mod-3 action penalty onto the throwing action.




old end text of the "Actions that do not require rolls" section:

If you try to perform non-roll actions last in the round, then you are limited by the "maximum action mod stack" value.
A 1a action normally requires that the action mod stack is not worse than mod-6. A 2a action normally requires MAMS-3.
A 3a action normally requires MAMS-0.



Old end text of "Time: actions and rounds" section:

Some actions take "rest of round" time to perform and requires that you do not do any other actions that round. They also usually have a limit to how severe the action mod stack is allowed to be for them to take "rest of round" instead of a full round. Usually this is mod-3 or mod-6.
E.g: if you have a base mod-1 from over encumbrance, then the first action will push another mod-3 onto the action stack, and the total is mod-4. This means that all "rest of round" actions that are limited to a stack of at most mod-3 will now take a full round instead.


old round and actions accounting:

actions & rounds accounting
---------------------------
One round can for reasons of accounting be considered as three actions long. This has nothing to do with the amount of actions you can perform in one turn, just that for some things it is good to be able to count actions in terms of turns and vice versa.
You can do as many actions as you have skill levels and modifiers for each turn, until your mod penalty stacks high enough that you cannot possibly succeed.
1 turn    =   3 actions
Just for bean counting.
This is sometimes used when counting speed up of things like reloading etc.




old interrupting and declining initiative:

declining initiative from action mod stack
------------------------------------------
Initiative for a battle is decided by dex+1d4. Initiative in each round is reduced by performing actions. Initiative is reduced by actions, but not by movement and other penalties. Thus it might be that slow characters can have higher initiative than fast characters later in the round, if they have performed fewer actions. Initiative is of course reset to initial value with a new round, when AMS is reset to 0.


interrupting with higher initiative
-----------------------------------
Characters can interrupt actions of slower opponents (lower initiative) as long as their initiative - ams is still +3 higher than the opponents current initiative - ams.

E.g: Rapid Rudolf (i13) wants to attack a target further off, but also wants to strike Sedate Sebastian (i7), who has declared attack on him. Since he has >=+3 higher initiative he can wait until Sedate Sebastian has moved into base contact, then interrupt Sebastian's attack by one of his own, thus saving movement points.
SS moves into base contact. RR interrupts and attacks, and is successful with a strike. SS chooses to parry the strike under "the right to react" rule. Then RR immediately moves out of base contact, towards his target further down the board.

E.g: Sigurd Slow (i6) is moving toward Fast Fabian (i11) to attack. Fast Fabian has higher initiative, but has an ams mod-3 from a prior attack on Distracting David. At the moment SS has i6-0=i6 and FF has i11-3=i8.
Fast Fabian can choose to go before Sigurd Slow, since he has higher initiative even with the ams mod, but he cannot choose to interrupt SS after moving in but before the attack, since his modified initiative is only +2 higher than SS.






old timing and pacing rule text:

rearrange action penalties
--------------------------
Players with the "timing" skill can rearrange action penalties;
e.g. 1st -3, 2nd -0, 3rd -6
E.g: Hero A wants to be defensive, and thus chooses to save his primary, unmodified, action for a later parry. He attacks with his secondary (mod -3) action. Later in the round monster B attacks him. He then uses his primary (mod -0) action to make a very safe parry. Then monster C also attacks. He now chooses to take another parry action, which is then his tertiary (mod -6) action. This is crappy odds, so he also uses the "yield" maneuver and backs away one square with a remaining movement point. Yield gives him a mod+3, so he then has mod-3 total for this second parry action.

Rearranging the penalties is a way to have the character focus more on some actions than others, e.g. "offensive/defensive stance", etc.


split action penalties
----------------------
Player with the "pacing" skill can split action penalties so that all or some actions in the round get the same penalties. The actions with split penalties get 2/3 of top penalty (round up):
2x -2 instead of 1st -0, 2nd -3                  (-2,-2,-6,-9)
3x -4 instead of 1st -0, 2nd -3, 3rd -6          (-4,-4,-4,-9)
4x -6 instead of 1st -0, 2nd -3, 3rd -6, 4th -9  (-6,-6,-6,-6)
and so on
Split penalty actions can also be rearranged around normal penalty actions. Keep track of the correct penalties though.
E.g. it is possible to take (-6, -2, -2, -9) with one split and two re-arrange permutation steps.

Just like with rearranging penalties, splitting mods is also a way of giving equal focus to some actions. There are then no primary and secondary actions, but two equal actions instead. E.g. striking a balance between offensive and defensive mode.








old MAMS:
maximum action modification stack (MAMS): Some actions and maneuvers cannot be attempted if the character already have a too severe action mod stack penalty. Usually, actions that take 2a to complete have MAMS-3, which means that they cannot be attempted if the character has already done too many actions before, and have a too severe action modification stack penalty.





old initiative interrupt
(basic version)
Characters with +3 higher initiative can interrupt slower characters' actions.
(advanced version)



old initiative interrupt
Characters with +3 higher initiative can interrupt slower characters if they succeed a roll of 10 + initiative diff - AMS.
(alternate advanced version)
E.g (adv): Sigurd Slow is moving toward Fast Fabian to attack. Fast Fabian has higher initiative, but has a mod-3 from a prior attack on Distracting David.
Fast Fabian can choose to go before Sigurd Slow, since he has higher initiative, or he can choose to interrupt Sigurd Slow just after Sigurd has moved into base contact but before he can make the attack. If Fabian wants to try interrupting he must succeed a 10-3=7 roll on a d10, or Sigurd will be able to make the attack first.


old charge extra
Additionally the user also gains a +1 mod to the primary attack for declaring a "run" movement and moving at least his walk+1 steps in a straight line (i.e. no waypoints) before encountering the target.


old bow reload style
If the bow is "unloaded" at the start of a round it takes a full round to reload, or a successful "quick draw" to reload in one action. If the quiver is one of the "special access" items for quick draw it can be reloaded in one action without a successful quick draw, or zero actions with a successful quick draw.


old stuff from block
The target can move past on a successful dex/dex mod diff (block success), but breaking through a block counts as an action. The target can also try to break through the block on a str/str mod diff (block success), and that also counts as an action.
If target is trying to break through the block, the blocker gets one attack at mod-3 "included" in the block action, i.e. no extra action.


old stuff from tackle writing attempts
If the tackle action roll succeeds:
The tackle roll is as follows: Roll for tackle. If it succeeds then roll a resistance roll:
attacker has movement/2 (round down) + str + diff (tackle) = vs value
defender has str. If the defender also has the tackle skill, he can choose to take an action to roll for his tackle and add the diff (success only) to his strength.
attacker (mov/2 + str + diff)  versus  defender (str + (diff))
If the attacker is successful he can push the defender out of the way one square. If the defender has movement points left he must roll a dex or go off balance, if he has no movement points left he automatically goes off balance.
If successful +0-+2 the target must succeed a dex roll or fall.
If successful +3-+5 the target takes 1 damage, penetrating 1, and must succeed a dex-3 or fall down.
If successful

str vs str mod diff (tackle). If the opponent also has tackle he can choose to react and take an action to roll for his tackle and add the diff to the above resistance roll.


Skill scf 1.0: "rapid reload bow" can reload a bow in "rest of round" with more severe action stack mods. Each skill level allows for one extra action stack mod beyond mod-3. E.g: "rrb"=5 can reload with action mod stack at mod-8.
At level 3 it is also possible to reload from scratch in 2a. Starting from an action mod stack of at most mod-6 (follows from above).
At level 6 it is also possible to reload from scratch in 1a. Starting from an action mod stack of at most mod-9 (follows form above).
At level 9 it is also possible to reload from scratch in 0a, i.e. taking no time and pushing no mod on the action stack.


Skill scf 3.0: "rapid reload crossbow" can reload a crossbow type weapon (crossbow, arbalest, ballista) faster than usual. Each skill level reduces the time to reload with one round.
If the modified reload time is reduced to "0r" it will take 2a. Starting from an action mod stack of
If it is reduced to "-1r" it takes 1a.
It if is reduced to "-2r" it takes 0a.
If the reload time is reduced to 0r it takes 1a to reload. If it is reduced one more step it takes 0a.


old grapple text:
Next round the grappler can try the sty/sty mod grapple diff as primary action to retain hold every round. Or the grappled can try to break free with the same setup. Either or, not both rolls though. Keeping a hold with grapple is a primary action. If the grappled also has grapple he can defend with that to break loose and then use his own grapple mod in the sty vs sty roll.
Grapple can also be attempted with mod-3 to silence the opponent. Grapple after successful sneak cannot be avoided/parried, and the target is automatically silenced if the attacker so wishes.
The during a hold the attacker can chose to inflict 1DX damage on the held target, where X is the unmodified success diff from the sty/sty.
E.g. Stalwart the Strong tries to grapple hold of Flexible Fredrick. SS dex5 str8, grapple 5, and FF dex8, str5: SS rolls 3 for grapple = diff+2, then rolls dex/dex +2 (grapple diff) (=5 vs 8 (=2) + 2 =4 to succeed with the grab) of 3



from the old grapple text:
Grapple is dex/dex mod + grapple diff, to first lock hold, then str/str mod + grapple diff each round to retain hold.
Grapple after successful sneak requires no dex/dex to lock hold, and target is automatically silenced if the attacker so wishes.



from end of initiative in basic rules (just reiterates what was already said):
In each round the ones with high initiative can choose when they want to do their actions. They can go before slower characters, or wait and then interrupt other's actions when it suits them. The faster can also split their different actions to fall between the actions of slower characters.



Reloading and firing with ranged weapons
----------------------------------------
Ranged weapons generally require reloading and aiming, giving a much lower "rate of fire" than melee weapons. On the other hand, they are generally impossible to parry.


Skill scf 0.5: "rapid reload" reduces the reload time by one "action step" for each skill step. For this purpose, each round is treated as three actions. So, three skill levels reduce the time by one round.
E.g. Reload time 2r is reduced to 0r2a by rapid reload level 4, and to 0r1a by rapid reload lvl 5. Reload time can never be reduced to less than 1a. And reload is non-roll action, and can not be penalty shuffled against consecutive actions.


Skill scf special : "attacks" allows for making more attacks each round. Each skill level of "attacks" allows for taking one attack action each round. This skill is thus required to make more than one attack per round. Everyone has "attacks"=1 for free by default, which allows them to make one attack each round. This skill has no effect on action penalties, they work just as normal. It is just to be able to take multiple attack actions.
E.g. Fredrick the Fast has "attacks"=3 and can thus try to push three attack actions each round, with the normal mod-0, mod-3, mod-6 action penalties, unless he tries to make other actions in between.
Each skill level of "attacks" costs 20xp.
When using "attacks" in conjunction with "double", one double attack is still only one attack, since it is only one action.


Skill scf 0.5 : "extra attacks" allows for the character to try to make extra attacks, after the first one, each round. This skill is not necessary for the first attack in each round. To attempt extra attacks, after the first, the character must roll for the extra attacks skill. This roll is modified by the normal action modification stack. If the attempt fails, the action is not wasted, and the character can choose to do something else with it, but not an attack.
E.g: Dastardly David has just attacked, and now wants to make a second attack. He is just maneuvering and thus has no action stack modification from movement. He now must roll "extra attacks" (6) at mod-3 (the action stack after the first attack) He rolls 2 (success+1) and can thus make a second attack.
E.g: Fredrik the Fast has "extra attacks"=8, he has already made a first attack, and a parry, and now, for action 3 he wants to try another attack. He has action stack mod-6 after the first two actions, and thus has only a chance of 2 to succeed with "extra attacks". The situation would be the same if he had already done two attacks before attempting the third.
Note that the "extra attacks" skill is always modified by the entire action modification stack just like the all other actions and action skills. This also means that skills like "quick" and "mobile" will reduce penalties also for "extra attacks", so instead of buying huge skill values of "extra attacks" you might want to buy a few levels in quick and mobile as well...


Two Weapons
-----------
Or one weapon, one shield, two shields. Wielded one in each hand. When successive actions are performed by alternating between the hands, then the user gets a mod+1.
E.g. Attacking with sword, primary action mod-0, defending with shield, secondary action mod-3, but, alternate hand, mod+1, total mod-2. Tertiary action, attack with sword, mod-6, alternate hand mod+1, total mod-5.
E.g. Two swords. Primary attack mod-0, secondary attack other sword mod-3 (action stack) mod+1 (alternating hand), total mod-2, tertiary attack total mod-5.
Shield parry bonuses already include the "two weapon" bonus.















